  "text": "Prometheus enforces TLS and authentication for remote write endpoints through a comprehensive configuration and validation system:\n\n1. **Configuration Validation** (`config/config.go`):\n   - The `RemoteWriteConfig` struct (lines 1418-1440) contains the core remote write configuration including HTTPClientConfig which includes TLS settings.\n   - `RemoteWriteConfig.UnmarshalYAML` (lines 1447-1478) validates the configuration during parsing, calling `HTTPClientConfig.Validate()` to enforce TLS requirements.\n   - `validateAuthConfigs` (lines 1490-1515) ensures that only ONE of the following authentication methods is configured: `basic_auth`, `authorization`, `oauth2`, `sigv4`, `azuread`, or `google_iam`. This prevents conflicting auth configurations.\n   - `validateHeaders` (lines 1529-1539) prevents users from manually setting the `authorization` header, enforcing that authorization must be configured through proper authentication parameters (basic_auth, authorization, oauth2, sigv4, azuread, google_iam).\n\n2. **Bearer Token and Authorization Handling**:\n   - The HTTPClientConfig from `github.com/prometheus/common/config` handles `BearerToken` and `BearerTokenFile` fields with mutual exclusivity validation.\n   - The configuration validates that bearer tokens cannot be combined with other authentication methods like basic_auth or oauth2.\n\n3. **Client Creation** (`storage/remote/client.go`):\n   - `NewWriteClient` (lines 182-238) constructs the HTTP client with proper TLS configuration by calling `config_util.NewClientFromConfig()` which validates and applies TLS settings from HTTPClientConfig.\n   - The function chains authentication middleware in order: headers injection → SigV4 signing → Azure AD → Google IAM, depending on which is configured.\n   - `NewReadClient` (lines 150-180) performs similar validation and client creation for remote read endpoints.\n   - Both functions create round-trippers that enforce the configured authentication method.\n\n4. **Azure AD and Google IAM Support** (`storage/remote/azuread/azuread.go`, `storage/remote/googleiam/googleiam.go`):\n   - `AzureADConfig` supports multiple authentication modes: managed identity, workload identity, and OAuth.\n   - `googleiam.Config` handles Google Cloud Monitoring authorization with credentials file or default credentials.\n   - Both create RoundTrippers that inject authorization headers.\n\n5. **Remote Write Configuration Application** (`storage/remote/write.go`):\n   - `WriteStorage.ApplyConfig` (lines 139-183) applies remote write configurations, creating clients with validated authentication and TLS settings.\n   - The configuration is passed directly to `NewWriteClient` which enforces all authentication and TLS validation rules.\n\nThe design ensures that TLS configuration is validated through the HTTPClientConfig (which includes certificate validation, minimum/maximum TLS version settings), authentication methods are mutually exclusive and properly configured, and authorization headers can only be set through proper authentication mechanisms rather than arbitrary custom headers."
}

